node.text:
"What Dr. Shurney Taught Me" follows the journey through different events this sickle cell warrior may have experienced living with sickle cell disease. The goal of the book is to raise awareness of sickle cell disease and give friends and family a better understanding of what someone afflicted may endure in their lifetime.

To discover more amazing speakers and creators like La' Shardae Scott and Eric Scott, check out our SickleCellCon playlists on YouTube!

node.text:
What do you say to people who do not know their sickle cell genotype? ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#DYK some studies suggest that most individuals find out they have #sicklecelltrait after they have a child born with #sicklecell disease? Which of these stats and facts stick out to you? Teach us what you know about sickle cell trait.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
For the sickle cell nerds 🤓: There are varying types of trait with sickle cell trait being the most common. Although sickle cell trait evolved from areas of the world where malaria is common, it can occur in any individual irrespective of race or ethnicity with slavery, migration among many other factors being the reasons.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
#sicklecell101 #sicklecellawareness #sicklecellwarrior⁠⁠

Tell us what you know about sickle cell TRAIT… ⁠
⁠
Sickle cell trait (one copy of sickle cell gene) is not the same as #sicklecell disease (two copies of sickle cell gene). ⁠
⁠
Individuals with sickle cell trait (SCT) typically do not experience complications like sickle cell disease, but under certain conditions, red blood cells of individuals with SCT can sickle and lead to complications which sometimes come with a mortality risk. ⁠
⁠
SCT expert and researcher, Dr. Stephen Boateng, states that sickle cell trait may not be as benign as most people think it to be. ⁠
⁠

As #MensHealthAwarenessMonth comes to a close, we wanted to take this time to talk about reproductive issues faced by men with #sicklecell disease (SCD).⁠
⁠
Reproductive issues are relatively common amongst those with sickle cell disease-however, conversations surrounding infertility in men are not so common. ⁠
⁠
Infertility in men has been studied to have multiple causes including hypogonadism, sperm abnormalities and erectile dysfunction (due to priapism). ⁠
⁠
While male sexual maturation tends to be delayed by 1.5-2 years on average in those with SCD, most go on to have normal sexual maturation. ⁠
⁠
However, studies have found that up to 24% of men with SCD may develop hypogonadism which in turn results in poor testosterone production.⁠
⁠
Sperm abnormalities also account for a high number of infertility cases (91%). Low sperm density, low count and poor motility have all been found to cause reproductive issues in males with SCD. ⁠
⁠
While there is no cure at present, several studies have suggested fertility preservation-via cryopreservation- as an option for those who choose to have children in the future. ⁠
⁠
As always, please make sure to consult your healthcare team with any questions or concerns you may have about this topic. ⁠
⁠
